		<item>
		<title>Let them fail</title>
		<link>http://facio.com/blog/2013/05/let-them-fail/</link>
		<comments>http://facio.com/blog/2013/05/let-them-fail/#comments</comments>
		<pubDate>Tue, 07 May 2013 12:00:20 +0000</pubDate>
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Dirk]]></dc:creator>
				<category><![CDATA[Uncategorized]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[advice]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[management]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[professional development]]></category>

		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://facio.com/?p=1063</guid>
		<description><![CDATA[<p>Let them fail High-achieving employees who combine a strong work ethic and good attention to detail tend to be hands-on managers. Typical, positive traits of good hands-on managers is their &#8220;showing&#8221; excellence in action to their employees, keeping their eye &#8230; <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/05/let-them-fail/">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&#8594;</span></a></p><p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/05/let-them-fail/">Let them fail</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<figure class="alignleft" style="width: 300px;"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-488" title="Let them fail" src="http://facio.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Let-Them-Fail.png" alt="Let them fail" /><br />
<figcaption>Let them fail</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>High-achieving employees who combine a strong work ethic and good attention to detail tend to be hands-on managers. Typical, positive traits of good hands-on managers is their &#8220;showing&#8221; excellence in action to their employees, keeping their eye on assignments and development plans, and pushing them to success. One of the down sides of this management style &#8211; that sometimes seems like a strength &#8211; is intervening to ensure their employees don&#8217;t fail.</p>
<p>Yes, preventing a failure of some sort in the moment is good for the system and assignment &#8211; in the moment. The challenge is, people need to be trusted and empowered to see something through to completion. Whether they succeed or fail, the process of going to the end and the learnings that they take from that are invaluable. Sure, they are also learning when watching someone more seasoned do it for them. But the real learning requires both watching and doing. In the early going, the doing is going to be wrong.</p>
<p>I know, I know: for people who pursue and achieve excellence it can be hard to watch that failing happen. But it is just part of the process. In the days of master craftsmen, it was understood that there would be some waste: of time, of materials. It was literally built into the expectations of the relationship with that apprentice. Just watching, no matter for how long, doesn&#8217;t get you all the way there. Those lessons so ingrained into generations of craftspeople have been lost as we all naturally careen through the workplace.</p>
<p>The reality is, failing is important. For young professionals, for children, for all of us who are doing new things &#8211; part of evolving beyond ignorance and clumsiness is feeling what it is like to fall down. When we see others who are struggling to figure something out, it might be hard not to help. And certainly, sometimes helping is good and important. But sometimes, every now and then, we also need to let them fail.</p>
<p>The post <a href="http://facio.com/blog/2013/05/let-them-fail/">Let them fail</a> appeared first on <a href="http://facio.com">Facio</a>.</p>]]></content:encoded>
